</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="53B947B7609821F10ECF01127A2E81E0" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7BF2654C8F60AE06F155AC9BE82138A8" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">General distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8F657640BE3A31A587CBAB6E0F43C3EE" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName id="5662053EF7B2066A52C13FA3E74EECD3" authorityName="Raf., New Fl. [Rafinesque] 4: 16" authorityYear="1836" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aizoaceae" genus="Sesuvium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sesuvium verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis id="3A56983E2CBBFE61CEDC3C65F4897CBA" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">Sesuvium verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in North Mexico and the southern part of the USA (
<bibRefCitation id="9BC9184FFFF2BCBB7B0435230763AECC" author="Ferren, WR" journalOrPublisher="4. Oxford University Press, New York, Oxford" pageId="33" pageNumber="78" pagination="80 - 81" refId="B20" refString="Ferren, WR, 2003. Sesuvium. In: Flora of North America, North of Mexico, Vol. 4. Oxford University Press, New York, Oxford: 80 - 81" title="Sesuvium." volumeTitle="Flora of North America, North of Mexico, Vol." year="2003">Ferren 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Outside of its native range in the New World, it is reported as an introduced species in South-West Asia: Bahrain (
<bibRefCitation id="7FE838B15869EAB6FA9D6357AC63A5EE" author="Verdcourt, B" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="37" pageNumber="82" refId="B84" refString="Verdcourt, B, 1985. An introduced Sesuvium (Aizoaceae) in Arabia. Kew Bulletin 40(1): 208." title="An introduced Sesuvium (Aizoaceae) in Arabia. Kew Bulletin 40 (1): 208." year="1985">Verdcourt 1985</bibRefCitation>
; see also specimens at BM! E! and K!), the eastern part of Saudi Arabia (
<bibRefCitation id="8DE9BD0417C6749AF271D9D845C7E8EF" author="Miller, AG" editor="Miller, AG" journalOrPublisher="l. University Press, Edinburgh" pageId="35" pageNumber="80" pagination="155 - 168" refId="B57" refString="Miller, AG, 1996. Aizoaceae. In: Miller, AG, Cope, TA, Eds., Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol. l. University Press, Edinburgh: 155 - 168" title="Aizoaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol." year="1996">Miller 1996</bibRefCitation>
; specimens at E!, K!), Iran (
<bibRefCitation id="A18EC841E200393BC69CDBC739F93141" author="Fadaie, F" journalOrPublisher="Iranian Journal of Botany" pageId="33" pageNumber="78" pagination="87 - 88" refId="B19" refString="Fadaie, F, Attar, F, Ghahreman, A, 2006. A new record of Aizoaceae (Sesuvium verrucosum Raf.) for the flora of Iran. Iranian Journal of Botany 12 (1): 87 - 88" title="A new record of Aizoaceae (Sesuvium verrucosum Raf.) for the flora of Iran." volume="12" year="2006">Fadaie et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
) and United Arab Emirates (collections from Sharjah, 2009, K!). As indicated on the sheets from Bahrain (collected by M. Cornes and A.M. Alder, 1983-1985, E!), 
<taxonomicName id="AB039984FE8CA7976A627EE604A99567" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis id="91297BFF40702715B683323987093F2C" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widespread species in irrigated areas and loamy sands. In Saudi Arabia, it is invasive in diverse inland plant communities including wastelands and salt pans (
<bibRefCitation id="7EFE28AB40100DA04FDCAA8FC2F2865A" author="Miller, AG" editor="Miller, AG" journalOrPublisher="l. University Press, Edinburgh" pageId="35" pageNumber="80" pagination="155 - 168" refId="B57" refString="Miller, AG, 1996. Aizoaceae. In: Miller, AG, Cope, TA, Eds., Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol. l. University Press, Edinburgh: 155 - 168" title="Aizoaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol." year="1996">Miller 1996</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="00E4057CC7E44CE78D47AEB656AFAB77" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
One record has to be added for Syria: small young plants with only a few flowers and flower buds (Syria, Adra, desert, 27 Mar 1931, 
<emphasis id="CC8B3B14E251D479769CDFAA8C8FA385" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">R. Gombault 1998</emphasis>
, P04583848!), previously reported as 
<taxonomicName id="A649DFEBD6A3F1DD1D23941B2FFF174D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. mesembryanthemoides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="mesembryanthemoides">
<emphasis id="DDFC0F6C31AFFE246A381F4EDFECA9A6" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. mesembryanthemoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35AA27937686E1345EB153E83A2948B4" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1600/036364417X694575" author="Bohley, K" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="32" pageNumber="77" pagination="124 - 147" refId="B9" refString="Bohley, K, Winter, PJD, Kadereit, G, 2017. A revision of Sesuvium (Aizoaceae, Sesuvioideae). Systematic Botany 42 (1): 124 - 147, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1600/036364417X694575" title="A revision of Sesuvium (Aizoaceae, Sesuvioideae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1600/036364417X694575" volume="42" year="2017">Bohley et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Surprisingly, 
<taxonomicName id="7BB9139EACD122514DD1F2E34F3B80C0" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis id="06AFFADE1C6E3BFD8F4CC9CE0917B06C" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in other regions of the world as well (re-identifications of AS): (1) North Vietnam (Tonkin, Hải 
<normalizedToken id="FA02C301420B0347128D0BB8B05ADA19" originalValue="Phòng">Phong</normalizedToken>
, sandy seashores, Jul 1908, 
<emphasis id="41B012768DB3253A5679AE7BE8D13190" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
Ch. 
<normalizedToken id="C81207791F687368045A2909D1815B24" originalValue="D’Alleizette">D'Alleizette</normalizedToken>
2723
</emphasis>
, L1693583!, a new record for Southeast Asia) and (2) Hawaii [USA], Oahu, 10 Aug 1967, 
<emphasis id="6168EBAAD8B7AD016A20BEC9A1823C93" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">D. Herbst 523</emphasis>
(L0717044!). Both specimens were initially identified by the collectors as 
<taxonomicName id="6FC40BFB5257B04FEC88DA5E7EAF9C2A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. portulacastrum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="portulacastrum">
<emphasis id="CD18AD8EC54AC45E44DC4A24926CEC74" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. portulacastrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="74124D8D6F6F6C62C8DB2FC4DCB6C72C" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">
Here, neophytic 
<taxonomicName id="50F5C71F8B97402C315F34026D9FF93A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis id="0D95BF52FADB503C4B2303954FEC0509" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is reported for the first time from Macaronesia (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AA358831FE044BE727E0244C14A1C990" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Distribution map of Sesuvium portulacastrum subsp. persoonii (circles) and S. verrucosum (stars)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.92.22205.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/179520" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">17</figureCitation>
), i.e. from 
<normalizedToken id="5E9940D828705A32CC16A6B8F0A13D31" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Vicente (Cape Verde) and Gran Canaria (Canary Islands, Spain). In Gran Canaria, the species is well-established and dominant in a dried-out riverbed and extends to the beach and young dunes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9C3BB5BD02291CA2963D52312AEA9256" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Sesuvium verrucosum: A green-leaved plants, B red-leaved plants. Photographs by F. Verloove (Gran Canaria, Canary Islands, Spain, spring 2017)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.92.22205.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/179523" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">20</figureCitation>
). So far, 
<taxonomicName id="0E7552A91AE0CAF6E9FA28F40717E3BD" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. verrucosum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="verrucosum">
<emphasis id="5630D18F465E610BEBB970860020A8D9" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="75">S. verrucosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been recorded in other suitable habitats in the area (pers. obs. by Marcos Salas-Pascual in 2016 and Filip Verloove in March and April 2017) and it remains unknown how the species was introduced. Due to the evident invasive character of this species, it may be found in other African countries.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C3A23E44ACC0D6130BB0CE8BFE0479EF" ID-Zenodo-Dep="1166642" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.92.22205.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/179523" pageId="30" pageNumber="75" start="Figure 20" startId="F20">
